Project Overview:

Our goal with this project was to design and develop a dice-based game called Dice Duel using Python and the Tkinter library.
The application simulates a turn-based game where a player competes against the house (computer) by rolling a six-sided die. 
The higher roll wins each round, and the overall objective is to be the first to win 10 rounds.

The expected outcome of the final product is a user-friendly graphical interface that clearly displays all game data, including dice rolls, round results, and score tracking.
The program was designed with simplicity in mind to ensure that users can easily understand and interact with the game without a steep learning curve.

Program Specifications:

Allow the user to initiate gameplay through a button click
Simulate a six sided dice roll for both the player and the house
Display both dice roll values in real time within the GUI
Determine the winner of each round based on the highest roll
Track and update the score for both the player and the house
Keep count of the total number of rounds played
Detect when a player reaches 10 wins and terminate the game
Display a message indicating the winner of the game
Provide a reset option

Game Rules:

Each round consists of one roll per player
The highest roll earns 1 point
Ties do not award points
The first player to reach 10 points wins the game

Technical Design:

Our program follows a modular structure that separates logic and interface

-Language: Python 3

-Framework: Tkinter for the graphical user interface

-Architecture: Two‑class, object‑oriented design

Layering:

- Game Logic Class
Handles dice rolling, score tracking, and game rules
Determines round outcomes and win conditions

- GUI Class
Handles layout, labels, and user interaction
Displays results and updates based on game logic

Aesthetics:
Uses a retro arcade theme with a dark background and neon colors to create a fun, engaging atmosphere.
- High‑contrast Lime text on black improves readability for all users.
- Interactive feedback (button highlights and disabled state at game end) guides the player through actions.
- Consistent spacing, frames, and centered layout keep the interface clean, organized, and user‑friendly.


